<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-421-835  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 421 835.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  Oct 1990 v8 n10 p94(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Dot matrix printers regroup under fire from lasers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cole, Patrick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The popularity of laser printers is putting pressure on dot matrixprinter manufacturers to add new features and lower prices.andP;  Laserprinters are now surpassing dot matrix printers in sales andlasers account for 43 percent of the market while dot matrixprinters account for 38 percent.andP;  In 1990, US dot matrix sales areexpected to drop for the first time, to $3.79 billion, and it ispredicted that by 1994 the market will decline by 31 percent, to$2.6 billion.andP;  Manufacturers are working to offer more fonts,build in more memory and boost speed.andP;  There is seriouscompetition between the two top dot matrix suppliers, EpsonAmerica and Panasonic Industrial.andP;  Panasonic sells almostone-fifth of all dot matrix printers and has edged out Epson asthe frontrunner.andP;  It is expected that there will be an emphasis onsales of dot matrix printers to small offices.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Epson America Inc. (products)Panasonic Industrial Co. (products).andO;Topic:     Dot-Matrix PrintersLaser PrintersCompetitionMarket AnalysisMarket Share.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Page printers outsell dot matrix devices. (graph)Panasonic overtakes Epson in dot matrix printer derby. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>